The body was waterlogged, and Talbot thought he saw tiny creatures swimming just beneath the skin.
The potential for true genetic symbiosis sparked his imagination, a being neither human nor sea-creature, but something so much more.
He grabbed a dead crab half-buried in the sand. The shell was cracked, and he used it to slice his neighbor's throat open.
The sand turned to black mud and the sight of what emerged made him cry out in terrified elation.
He closed his eyes and spread his arms, ready to receive whatever fate would befall him.
His hands explored his face, and the strange mask that was suddenly wearing.
His heart was racing. He could remember putting on this costume. What did it all mean?
There were screams and roars coming from all around him. And they were getting closer.
It felt cold against her skin, like the final caress of death.
She was fascinated by the hands in front of her, and the skull they were holding.
Something was approaching, and her instincts told her to run.
She couldn't recognize the materials used to make her mask, and wondered how it came to be.
A man wearing the same outfit crawled towards her, bleeding. The chill returned as she realized they were wearing a uniform.
She bent down to help to bleeding man when she heard something in the distance running towards them.
He could barely see out of one eye, his hands running over the red crystal that was fused to his mask.
He felt a round plate pressing into his back. His fingers fumbled around the edges, trying to decipher the strange etchings.
Whatever the meaning behind these clothes, he understood immediately the danger he was in.
She was caught off-guard by the mask on her face. Where did it come from?
She'd never seen anyone wear anything like this. Where did these clothes come from?
She didn't know which way to run. The footsteps were coming from her left and right.
The mask fit her face perfectly. She knew enough about cosplay to know how hard that was to do.
The costume reminded her of a game she had played long ago. Perhaps this was a different kind of game?
Suddenly a group of people all wearing the same costume ran past. She didn't think twice about following them.
The metallic mask felt finely made, luxurious and menacing in equal measure.
How did she come to be dressed in such ornate clothing? And how was it a perfect fit?
This was no time to admire her new outfit. She could sense a different kind of danger lurking nearby.
He could see a multitude of colors in his peripheral vision, only realizing a moment later that he was wearing a mask.
David knew a uniform when he saw one, and this one fit him perfectly.
In front of him was a group of people dressed just like him, repairing a broken generator.
He felt the spikes protruding from his helmet, ignoring the pain as he sliced open a fingertip.
He heard movement nearby, and his desire for bloodshed ignited.
He expected to find a sacrifice waiting for him, but was surprised when he locked eyes with a kindred spirit instead.
He wished he could see how fearsome he looked in this strange new mask.
He didn't question the clothes he was wearing. He knew it was all for a higher purpose.
He revved his chainsaw, wondering when he'd meet his new friend.
He stood before a sinister figure in a spiky red mask, and quickly realized he was wearing a similar mask.
Whoever this was, they were here for a similar purpose. A voice inside told him they would have to work together.
Together they forged ahead, their connection strong and unspoken.
She could see without seeing and was taken aback by her own appearance.
She never imagined such finery could ever exist, much less be made for her to wear.
The screams of past patients rang in her ears as she readied her latest instrument of pain.
She imagined stalking the forests of her homeland, menacing the invaders with this blood-red mask.
A worthy sacrifice suddenly ran by, and she quickly pulled out a hatchet.

She was leaving her hometown for the last time, adrift and in need of guidance.

The rooster vanished into the flames, and the power it held over him was broken.
It was his favorite recording, a beautiful melody formed of screams and crows.
